KYASANUR FOREST DISEASE - INDIA: BACKGROUND
*******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
See Also
Kyasanur Forest Disease - India 20000322222257
Date: Thu, 23 Mar 2000 05:59:30 +0200
From: Stephen Berger <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>

The following background data on Kyasanur Forest disease were extracted
from GIDEON <http://www.cyinfo.com>
Agent: VIRUS - (RNA - Flaviviridae)
Reservoirs: rodent, shrew, monkey, bat, bird, tick
Vectors: ticks (_Haemaphylsalis spinigera_, _H. turturis_, _H. papuana_
[_kinneari_)
Vehicle: none
Incubation Period: 3d - 12d
Clinical Hints:
Myalgia, vomiting, conjunctivitis, relative bradycardia, generalized
lymphadenopathy, palatal vesicles, leukopenia and thrombocytopenia;
encephalitis occasionally encountered; patient may recall tick bite during
the preceding 12 days.
- The disease is endemic only to India.
- KFD was first described in 1957 in the Kyasanur Forest of Karnataka
State. Most cases are reported from Karnataka (Shimoga, northern and
southern Kanara and Chikmagalur districts). Rates peak during January to
February.
- Epidemics were reported during 1982 to 1983, with 326 cases (29 fatal) in
1983. 88 152 persons in an endemic area were vaccinated during 1990 to 1992.
- Local reservoirs include black-faced langurs (_Presbytis entellus_),
macaques
(_Macaca radiata_), shrews (_Suncus murinus_), rats (_Rattus wroughtoni_),
birds,
squirrels and bats.
- The appearance of dead monkeys in the endemic area may herald an epidemic.
--
Steve Berger
Geographic Medicine
Tel Aviv Medical Center
